I managed to find a working solution to this, which I&#39;ve currently tested with Pages, not controllers and views.

**Required Interfaces**

 - `IActionDescriptorCollectionProvider` - Provides a list of all Razor pages.
 - `PageLoader` - Loads a Razor page, resolves its security policies and class attributes.
 - `IAuthorizationService`- Determines if the user is authorized to a policy.

**Steps**

Get a list of all razor pages.

    var pageDescriptors = _descriptorProvider.ActionDescriptors.Items
      .OfType&lt;PageActionDescriptor&gt;()
      .ToArray();

Loop through the pages and load each one:

    var compiledPage = await _pageLoader.LoadAsync(pageDescriptor);

At this point you can do some processing based on attributes that are added to the page model. Note that **any attribute that you add to the page model class will be automatically resolved in the `EndpointMetadata`**, no need to do custom reflection work!

    var pageMetadata = compiledPage.EndpointMetadata
      .OfType&lt;PageMetadataAttribute&gt;() // My custom attribute.
      .FirstOrDefault();

Note that policies and authorization will be added to the Razor page metadata in the form of an `AuthorizeAttribute` instance.

Extract the authorize attributes, loop through them and evaluate.

    var authorization = compiledPage.EndpointMetadata
      .OfType&lt;AuthorizeAttribute&gt;()
      .ToArray();
    
    foreach (var auth in authorization)
    {
      if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(auth.Policy))
      {
        var authResult = await _authorizationService.AuthorizeAsync(
          _httpContextAccessor.HttpContext.User,
          auth.Policy);
    
